  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>YouTube Shorts</strong> are vertical-format videos up to 3 minutes long that are surfaced in a dedicated swipe-feed on YouTube. They run on a separate discovery algorithm from long-form content, are monetised through a shared ad revenue pool (creators receive 45%), and can be created in-app or uploaded. Shorts represent YouTube's competitive response to TikTok and Instagram Reels.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">YT Shorts, Vertical Video</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">7 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">YouTube Shorts give channels a second discovery engine entirely. A long-form channel with stagnant subscriber growth can use Shorts to reach entirely new audiences, then funnel the most engaged viewers back to their main content. The two formats are complementary, not competing.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are YouTube Shorts?</h2>
        <p>YouTube Shorts are videos that meet two criteria: they are in a vertical aspect ratio (9:16), and they are 3 minutes or shorter. Videos meeting these criteria are automatically identified as Shorts by YouTube and distributed in the Shorts feed rather than the standard video recommendation system.</p>
        <p>Shorts appear in three places on YouTube:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The Shorts shelf</strong> on the YouTube homepage</li>
          <li><strong>The dedicated Shorts feed</strong> (accessible via the Shorts icon in the bottom navigation on mobile)</li>
          <li><strong>The channel's Shorts tab</strong> (separate from the Videos tab)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Unlike long-form YouTube videos, which can be watched in the embedded player on any device, Shorts are optimised for full-screen mobile viewing and are primarily consumed by swiping up through an infinite scroll feed.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">2024 length update</div>
          <p>In October 2024, YouTube extended the maximum Shorts length from 60 seconds to <strong>3 minutes</strong>. This matches Instagram Reels' maximum length and gave creators more flexibility for tutorials, explainers, and multi-step content that didn't fit in 60 seconds.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="algorithm">How the YouTube Shorts algorithm works</h2>
        <p>The Shorts algorithm is fundamentally different from the long-form algorithm. Where long-form success depends heavily on click-through rate from thumbnails and search ranking, Shorts success is almost entirely driven by <strong>viewer satisfaction signals within the feed</strong>.</p>
        <p>The algorithm's primary ranking signals for Shorts:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Completion rate (most important).</strong> What percentage of viewers watch the Short all the way to the end? Higher completion = more distribution. A 90% completion rate Short will outperform a 40% completion rate Short regardless of absolute view count.</li>
          <li><strong>Swipe-away rate (inverse signal).</strong> How quickly are viewers swiping past the video? A high early swipe-away rate tells the algorithm the content is not resonating with the audience it's being shown to.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-watch rate.</strong> Shorts that users replay (the video loops automatically) signal high satisfaction and get amplified further.</li>
          <li><strong>Likes and comments.</strong> Secondary signals that confirm engagement quality, but less important than completion rate.</li>
          <li><strong>Shares.</strong> Shorts that get shared to external platforms receive a strong positive signal — it means the content resonated enough for someone to spread it beyond YouTube.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="vs-longform">YouTube Shorts vs long-form: key differences</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>YouTube Shorts</th><th>Long-Form Video</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Max length</strong></td><td>3 minutes</td><td>12 hours</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Discovery</strong></td><td>Swipe feed (algorithm-first)</td><td>Search + recommendations</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Thumbnail</strong></td><td>No (frame-based preview)</td><td>Yes (critical for CTR)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Ad revenue split</strong></td><td>Creator 45%, YouTube 55%</td><td>Creator 55%, YouTube 45%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>YPP watch hours</strong></td><td>Does not count toward 4,000 hrs</td><td>Counts toward 4,000 hrs</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Key metric</strong></td><td>Completion rate</td><td>Average view duration + CTR</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Comments</strong></td><td>Shown below (mobile), fewer</td><td>Prominent comment section</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices for YouTube Shorts in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Hook in the first 1-2 seconds.</strong> Unlike long-form where the title brings pre-qualified viewers, Shorts are shown cold to people who may have no idea who you are. The first frame must stop the swipe. Open with a visual surprise, a bold statement, or a question.</li>
          <li><strong>Aim for 90%+ completion rate.</strong> Structure content so there's a reason to stay until the end — a punchline, a reveal, a result, or a practical tip payoff. Never pad Shorts to fill time.</li>
          <li><strong>Use captions.</strong> A large proportion of Shorts are watched without sound, especially in the initial scroll. On-screen captions (burned in or via YouTube's auto-captions) significantly improve comprehension and completion rate for silent viewers.</li>
          <li><strong>Film for 9:16 from the start.</strong> Cropped horizontal videos perform worse because key visual information often gets cut off. If repurposing long-form content, reframe deliberately — don't just crop.</li>
          <li><strong>Post consistently, not just occasionally.</strong> YouTube's Shorts algorithm rewards active Shorts channels. 3-5 Shorts per week generally outperforms 1 Short per month in terms of sustained reach growth.</li>
          <li><strong>Use trending audio strategically.</strong> YouTube, like TikTok, surfaces Shorts that use trending audio to more viewers. Check the Shorts creation tool for trending sounds. Use them when the audio fits the content naturally — forced fits perform poorly.</li>
          <li><strong>End with a CTA toward long-form.</strong> The most sustainable Shorts strategy is using Shorts as a top-of-funnel that directs engaged viewers to long-form content. End Shorts with a "Watch the full video" or "Check the link in my bio" prompt.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor retention analytics per Short.</strong> YouTube Studio shows a moment-by-moment retention graph for Shorts. Identify where viewers are swiping away and rework the pacing or hook of future Shorts accordingly.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Shorts and subscriber quality</div>
          <p>Shorts can grow subscriber counts quickly, but Shorts-driven subscribers often have lower long-form engagement than subscribers gained through search or recommended long-form videos. Track which subscriber sources convert to long-form viewers, not just total subscriber count.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="for-brands">YouTube Shorts for brand channels</h2>
        <p>Brand-owned channels often struggle with Shorts because branded content lacks the entertainment or education value that drives high completion rates in the swipe feed. The most effective brand Shorts formats are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Quick tutorials or how-tos</strong> that demonstrate product use in under 60 seconds</li>
          <li><strong>Before/after transformations</strong> with strong visual contrast</li>
          <li><strong>Rapid-fire tip lists</strong> (e.g., "3 mistakes everyone makes with X")</li>
          <li><strong>Behind-the-scenes clips</strong> that humanise the brand</li>
          <li><strong>Repurposed long-form highlights</strong> — the single most interesting 45 seconds of a longer video, edited to stand alone</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Brands should avoid: talking-head corporate announcements, product advertisement-style Shorts with no value, and long intros that delay the core content.</p>

        <h2 id="monetisation">Shorts monetisation deep dive</h2>
        <p>The Shorts monetisation model is distinct from long-form. YouTube pools all ad revenue generated across the Shorts feed in a given month, takes a portion for music licensing costs (when creators use licensed music), then distributes the remainder to eligible creators based on their proportional share of total Shorts views.</p>
        <p>Key facts about Shorts monetisation:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Creators keep <strong>45% of their allocated revenue</strong> (not 55% as with long-form)</li>
          <li>Shorts using licensed music from the YouTube Audio Library have a portion of their allocation redirected to rights holders</li>
          <li>Original audio Shorts (no licensed music) retain the full 45% creator share</li>
          <li>Shorts revenue is typically much lower per-view than long-form — Shorts are a growth tool, not a primary revenue source for most creators</li>
          <li>Fan funding features (Super Thanks, memberships) are available to Shorts-eligible YPP members</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common YouTube Shorts mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No hook.</strong> Starting with a logo, intro animation, or "Hey guys welcome back" kills completion rate instantly in a swipe environment.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating Shorts as an afterthought.</strong> Repurposing without editing produces Shorts that look like they were cropped as an afterthought. The best performing Shorts were designed as Shorts from the start.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring completion rate in favour of view count.</strong> A Short with 50,000 views and 30% completion will get less distribution than one with 5,000 views and 95% completion.</li>
          <li><strong>Not linking to long-form content.</strong> Shorts without a call to action leave reach on the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting inconsistently.</strong> Two Shorts in January and nothing until April generates no algorithmic momentum.</li>
        </ul>

